⚙️ Full Auth0 Terraform Import Command Reference

Each Auth0 resource type has:

Its Terraform resource type

The naming convention in your .tf (left-hand side)

The import ID (what you’ll get from the Auth0 dashboard or API)

And the example command for importing it.

🧱 1. Applications (Clients)
Purpose:

Represents apps registered in Auth0 (Web App, SPA, Native, M2M, etc.)

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Applications → [Your App] → Settings → Client ID

Terraform Resource:

auth0_client

Example:
terraform import auth0_client.web_app nKOqzkFxgHkhYu5PyJWJnXlpxgYM7byC

🌐 2. APIs (Resource Servers)
Purpose:

Represents APIs that define permissions (scopes) your apps can request.

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → APIs → [Your API] → Settings → API Identifier
(ID = UUID visible in URL or from Auth0 Management API)

Terraform Resource:

auth0_resource_server

Example:
terraform import auth0_resource_server.api_server 68f420a69642a3ee0c07248d

🔑 3. Database Connections
Purpose:

Represents your Auth0-hosted user database (“Username-Password-Authentication”).

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Authentication → Database → [Your DB Connection] → Name

Terraform Resource:

auth0_connection

Example:
terraform import auth0_connection.db_connection Username-Password-Authentication

🧍‍♂️ 4. Social Connections
Purpose:

Integrations with social providers like Google, GitHub, Facebook, etc.

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Authentication → Social → [Provider] → Name

Terraform Resource:

auth0_connection

Example:
terraform import auth0_connection.google_oauth2 google-oauth2

🏢 5. Enterprise Connections
Purpose:

Enterprise IdPs (AD, SAML, OIDC, Azure AD, etc.)

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Authentication → Enterprise → [Connection] → Name

Terraform Resource:

auth0_connection

Example:
terraform import auth0_connection.azure_ad_connection my-azuread-connection

🔄 6. Actions
Purpose:

Custom scripts that run during Auth0 flows (post-login, pre-user registration, etc.)

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Actions → Library → [Action] → URL contains ID

Terraform Resource:

auth0_action

Example:
terraform import auth0_action.post_login_action act_2bGx4Yn4Jx8g3bWc

⚙️ 7. Triggers (Action Bindings)
Purpose:

Defines when a specific action executes (binding between trigger & action).

Where to find the ID:

Usually managed as part of the action in dashboard; Terraform ID = trigger type.

Terraform Resource:

auth0_trigger_binding

Example:
terraform import auth0_trigger_binding.post_login_binding post-login

🧩 8. Rules (Legacy system)
Purpose:

Older scripting system before Actions (still widely used).

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Actions → Rules (Legacy) → Rule name or via API.

Terraform Resource:

auth0_rule

Example:
terraform import auth0_rule.add_custom_claims_rule rul_xKsj8jh62KLJHJ

🧑‍💼 9. Roles
Purpose:

RBAC roles that group permissions for users or applications.

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → User Management → Roles → [Role] → URL

Terraform Resource:

auth0_role

Example:
terraform import auth0_role.admin_role rol_p2rWJuk3sRg0J7vH

🔒 10. Permissions (API Scopes)
Purpose:

Permissions defined inside an API (resource server).

Where to find the ID:

Inside API → “Permissions” tab → scope names (part of auth0_resource_server definition)

⚠️ You don’t import these separately — they come with the auth0_resource_server resource.

👥 11. Organizations
Purpose:

B2B feature for grouping users and tenants.

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Organizations → [Org] → URL contains ID

Terraform Resource:

auth0_organization

Example:
terraform import auth0_organization.acme_org org_t3HyxK35AkzFwUsB

📄 12. Custom Domains
Purpose:

Your custom branded login domain (e.g. login.mycompany.com).

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Branding → Custom Domains → ID in URL

Terraform Resource:

auth0_custom_domain

Example:
terraform import auth0_custom_domain.custom_login_domain cd_1a2b3c4d5e6f7g8h

📧 13. Email Templates
Purpose:

Custom email templates for signup, verification, password reset, etc.

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Branding → Email Templates → Choose Template (type)

Terraform Resource:

auth0_email_template

Example:
terraform import auth0_email_template.verification_email verify_email

📤 14. Log Streams
Purpose:

For sending logs to external systems (Datadog, Splunk, AWS EventBridge, etc.)

Where to find the ID:

Dashboard → Monitoring → Log Streams → [Stream] → URL

Terraform Resource:

auth0_log_stream

Example:
terraform import auth0_log_stream.datadog_stream lst_2bVx4Yn4Jx8g3bWc

🧭 15. Branding Settings
Purpose:

Controls Universal Login settings (colors, logos, page templates).

Where to find the ID:

Automatically managed — no manual ID needed, just import via tenant name.

Terraform Resource:

auth0_branding

Example:
terraform import auth0_branding.branding_settings branding

🧾 16. Tenant Settings
Purpose:

Global Auth0 tenant settings (friendly name, default directory, etc.)

Where to find the ID:

Applies to the entire tenant — no unique ID, just use "tenant" as key.

Terraform Resource:

auth0_tenant

Example:
terraform import auth0_tenant.tenant tenant

